---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import { meta } from "../lib/data.js";
import { num, url } from "../lib/format.js";

const m = meta();
const c = m.counts ?? {};
---

<Base title="About" description="What JUDGMENT is: the dataset, the models, and the live preregistered forecast registry.">
  <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
  <h1>What this is</h1>
  <p class="lede" style="max-width:76ch">
    JUDGMENT is the complete voting record of the Supreme Court of the United
    States — {num(c.cases)} cases and {num(c.vote_records)} individual justice
    votes across the {c.first_term}–{c.last_term} terms, every one browsable —
    plus a statistical engine that forecasts how the Court will rule, publishing
    calibrated probabilities for every pending case <i>before</i> it is decided
    and scoring itself as decisions land.
  </p>

  <h2>The data</h2>
  <p class="lede" style="max-width:76ch">
    The backbone is the <a href="http://scdb.wustl.edu" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Supreme
    Court Database</a> (Spaeth, Epstein, Martin, Segal, Ruger &amp; Benesh — the
    canonical source for case and vote records, gratefully used with attribution).
    Because SCDB is released annually, the term in progress is filled provisionally
    from <a href="https://www.oyez.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Oyez</a> and
    <a href="https://www.courtlistener.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CourtListener</a>,
    and — same-day — by parsing the Court's own slip-opinion syllabi, validation-gated
    against independently coded lineups. Oral-argument questioning comes from Oyez's
    structured transcripts ({num(7023)} argued cases since 1955); justice biographies
    combine hand-curated records with the Federal Judicial Center's directory. Every
    layer is regenerable from public sources by the pipeline in the repository, and
    provisional records are replaced wholesale when SCDB's annual release arrives.
  </p>

  <h2>The model</h2>
  <p class="lede" style="max-width:76ch">
    One rule governs the modeling: <b>no feature the forecaster could not have known
    at forecast time, and no evaluation that peeks</b>. Everything is validated
    walk-forward — train on the past, predict the next term, repeat across seven
    decades — with prospectively fitted isotonic calibration and a coalition model
    that replaces the usual (and wrong) assumption that nine votes are independent.
    Forecasts are staged: a <b>cert-stage</b> forecast from grant-time features
    freezes on argument day, and a separately scored <b>post-argument</b> stage adds
    per-justice questioning features from the transcripts plus the side the
    Solicitor General supports as amicus — the strongest signal the gate has ever
    passed. Features that failed it — question text (twice), nomination-time
    ideology scores, the originating circuit, dissent below — stayed out, and the
    negative results are documented alongside the wins.
  </p>

  <h2>The registry</h2>
  <p class="lede" style="max-width:76ch">
    Every forecast is timestamped in the public git history — preregistration by
    version control. The scorer admits nothing that is not strictly ex-ante: a
    forecast written on or after decision day is excluded from the
    <a href={url("/predict")}>track record</a>, never counted. The claims this site
    makes will be confirmed or embarrassed in public, automatically.
  </p>

  <h2>Code, data, and citation</h2>
  <p class="lede" style="max-width:76ch">
    Everything lives at
    <a href="https://github.com/KaraZajac/JUDGMENT" target="_blank" rel="noopener">github.com/KaraZajac/JUDGMENT</a> —
    pipeline, models, this site, the methods paper draft, and every validation
    artifact. Releases are archived on Zenodo under concept DOI
    <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21211376" target="_blank" rel="noopener">10.5281/zenodo.21211376</a>,
    which always resolves to the latest version. Code is MIT; the derived dataset is
    CC-BY-NC-4.0 with layered attribution documented in DATA-RIGHTS.md. Cite via
    CITATION.cff in the repository.
  </p>

  <p class="lede" style="max-width:76ch">
    Built and maintained by Kara Zajac
    (<a href="https://orcid.org/0009-0001-7400-1394" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ORCID
    0009-0001-7400-1394</a>). Sources current as of SCDB {m.scdb?.modern_release}
    with provisional coverage through the term in progress.
  </p>
</Base>
